\i\fs32 \cf9 \cb10 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
To provide confidentiality and key management \'96 the session symmetric key can be redistributed between parties using asymmetric key encryption where sender takes public key of receiver and encrypts session key. Only specific receiver can decrypt session key by using its own private key. This is used by SSL protocol to establish secure connection between client and server using standard web browser.
\i0 \cb1 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\i \cb10 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Digital signature can utilise public key infrastructure to provide message integrity and at the same time authenticate the sender. The sender creates hash signature of the message and encrypts that signature with its own private key. Both message and encrypted hash signature is send to its destination. The receiver recalculates the hash signature of the message and decrypts appended hash signature with sender\'92s public key. If both hash signatures are the same then the integrity of the message is checked that no changes were made and at the same time authentication of the sender has been performed
\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

