\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf7 \cb8 Explain the role of Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) in modern communication systems. As part of your answer discuss the possible security issues related to HMAC.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb3 In HMAC, hashes are computed based on not only the inputted message but also a special Hashing key. In order to compute the same hash from the same message, it must be computed using the right hashing key.\cb1 \
\cb3 HMAC may be vulnerable if the underlying hashing algorithm is not sufficiently secure; sha-1 or md5 for example are not considered secure.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs48 \cf9 \cb10 Feedback\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\i\fs32 \cf9 \cb10 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
In cryptography, a keyed-hash message authentication code (HMAC) is a specific construction for calculating a message authentication code (MAC) involving a cryptographic hash function in combination with a secret cryptographic key. As with any MAC, it may be used to simultaneously verify both the data integrity and the authentication of a message.
\i0 \cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0
\i \cb10 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
No known extensions attacks have been found against the current HMAC specification because the outer application of the hash function masks the intermediate result of the internal hash.
\i0 \cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0
\i \cb10 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The cryptographic strength of the HMAC depends upon the size of the secret key that is used. The most common attack against HMACs is brute force to uncover the secret key. HMACs are substantially less affected by collisions than their underlying hashing algorithms alone. Therefore, HMAC-MD5 does not suffer from the same weaknesses that have been found in MD5
\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

